{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614500"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16369"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16369"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9060"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64905"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9060"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16369"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50339"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"916"},{"type":"tags","id":"1933"},{"type":"tags","id":"2089"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5931"},{"type":"tags","id":"7198"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21539"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21545"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64905"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with progressive symptoms over several months. He initially presented with right-sided tinnitus and unsteadiness. He now reports right-sided hearing loss and altered taste sensation. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals loss of taste sensation in the anterior two-thirds of the tongue on the right side. MRI scanning shows a mass lesion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely site of origin of this tumour?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Foramen ovale","Superior orbital fissure","Internal auditory meatus","Jugular foramen","Hypoglossal canal"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is classic for an acoustic neuroma (vestibular schwannoma), which typically arises from the \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal auditory meatus\u003C/strong\u003E. The progression of symptoms from unilateral tinnitus and unsteadiness to hearing loss and facial nerve involvement is characteristic of this slow-growing tumour affecting cranial nerve VIII and subsequently cranial nerve VII.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eforamen ovale\u003C/strong\u003E transmits the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve (V3). Tumours here would cause jaw weakness and altered sensation in the lower face, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior orbital fissure\u003C/strong\u003E contains cranial nerves III, IV, V1 and VI. Lesions here typically cause ophthalmoplegia, ptosis, and altered sensation in the upper face, none of which are described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ejugular foramen\u003C/strong\u003E transmits cranial nerves IX, X, and XI. Tumours in this location would cause dysphagia, hoarseness, and shoulder weakness, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal canal\u003C/strong\u003E transmits cranial nerve XII. Lesions here would cause tongue weakness and deviation, which are not described in this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe altered taste sensation in the anterior two-thirds of the tongue indicates involvement of the chorda tympani branch of the facial nerve (VII), which commonly occurs when acoustic neuromas grow large enough to affect adjacent structures. The combination of audiovestibular symptoms and facial nerve involvement strongly supports the diagnosis of an acoustic neuroma arising from the internal auditory meatus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acoustic neuromas typically present with unilateral hearing loss, tinnitus, and vestibular symptoms due to compression of cranial nerve VIII.","The internal auditory meatus is the most common location for acoustic neuromas (vestibular schwannomas).","Loss of taste in anterior two-thirds of tongue indicates involvement of cranial nerve VII, which commonly occurs with large acoustic neuromas."],"references":["Sheikh MM, De Jesus O. Vestibular Schwannoma. 2023 Aug 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32965983.","Gupta VK, Thakker A, Gupta KK. Vestibular Schwannoma: What We Know and Where We are Heading. Head Neck Pathol. 2020 Dec;14(4):1058-1066. doi: 10.1007/s12105-020-01155-x. Epub 2020 Mar 30. PMID: 32232723; PMCID: PMC7669921.","Marinelli JP, Beeler CJ, Carlson ML, Caye-Thomasen P, Spear SA, Erbele ID. Global Incidence of Sporadic Vestibular Schwannoma: A Systematic Review. Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2022 Aug;167(2):209-214. doi: 10.1177/01945998211042006. Epub 2021 Aug 31. PMID: 34464224."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50339"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16369"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50339"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T21:33:44+10